{
  "analysis": "This question is a red flag disguised as a technical decision. You're asking me to evaluate rewriting a service in Rust, but you've given me zero context about what service we're talking about, what language it's currently written in, what problems it has, who maintains it, how critical it is, or what resources are available. This is exactly how organizations make catastrophically expensive decisions.\n\nWithout knowing the current service's performance characteristics, bug history, team expertise, deployment complexity, dependencies, or business criticality, any recommendation is pure speculation. Are we talking about a weekend script or the payment processing backbone? A team of Rust experts or junior developers who barely know the current stack?\n\nThe biggest risk here isn't technical - it's organizational. Rewrites are where projects go to die. They consistently take 2-3x longer than estimated, introduce new categories of bugs, and often end up recreating the same architectural problems in a different language. Meanwhile, the old system accumulates technical debt because 'we're rewriting it anyway.'\n\nRust specifically carries additional risks: steep learning curve, longer development cycles, smaller talent pool for hiring, and ecosystem churn. The benefits - memory safety, performance - only matter if those are actual problems you're solving, not theoretical ones.",
